From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-14
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v126 — write TX_CTRL config bits (8+16) on engine start

Through v82..v125 the TX DMA engine never fetched descriptors despite
ring base addresses being programmed correctly and bit-0 "go" being
asserted on BAR+0x034.  v125 BAR0 telemetry confirmed: TX current
pointer (BAR+0x03c) stays at base across many xmit attempts → HW
never reads our descriptors.

Ghidra decompile of Orbis FW 12.02 reveals the missing piece:

  mts_mac_init @ ffffffffc85ecb60:
      *BAR+0x030 = 0x10100    ← MAC_MODE (Linux already does this)

  mts_init_rings_kick @ ffffffffc85ef1b0:
      *BAR+0x034 |= 1         ← TX engine GO
      *BAR+0x038 |= 1         ← RX engine GO

The Orbis BAR0 snapshot from a running idle interface shows BOTH
0x030 AND 0x034 at 0x00010100.  Linux's MTS_MAC_MODE write puts the
value at 0x030 only; the v125 snapshot in Linux shows BAR+0x034 = 0x4
(just bit 2 "kick") after MAC init — confirming 0x030 and 0x034 are
SEPARATE registers, despite appearing as a mirrored pair in the Orbis
dump.

Hypothesis: TX_CTRL (BAR+0x034) requires the same persistent config
bits 8+16 (= 0x00010100) before HW accepts the bit-0 "go".  Without
these bits, HW silently auto-clears bit 0 and never starts the DMA
fetch sequence.  This explains why every iteration since v82 left
tx_cons stuck at 0 — Linux was asking the engine to GO without ever
configuring it.

This patch writes 0x10101 (cfg bits 8+16 + go bit) in one transaction
at engine-start time in mts_open.  HW should accept the go bit, clear
it, and leave 0x10100 in the register — matching the Orbis steady
state seen in the snapshot.  RX_CTRL (BAR+0x038) is left as-is since
RX already works.

After this lands and is tested, the expected signal in dmesg is:
  v126: TX_CTRL 0x00000000 -> writel(|0x10101) -> 0x00010100

And practically:
  - dmesg: tx_cons starts advancing past tx_prod (was stuck at 0)
  - ip link enp0s20f1: TX bytes/packets non-zero
  - ping out succeeds
  - speedtest upload works
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c | 34 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 33 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -1970,8 +1970,40 @@ static int mts_open(struct net_device *ndev)
 		 rx_ctrl_before, readl(mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL));

 	/* 3. Start engines with empty rings → MAC's link-detect state
-	 *    machine samples PHY MII status now (no datapath work yet). */
-	writel(readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL) | 0x1, mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+	 *    machine samples PHY MII status now (no datapath work yet).
+	 *
+	 * v126: Orbis Ghidra dump confirms TX_CTRL (BAR+0x034) needs
+	 * persistent config bits 8+16 (= 0x00010100) before the bit-0 "go"
+	 * pulse is honoured.  Without those bits, HW accepts the go bit
+	 * (auto-clears it) but never starts the TX DMA fetch.  v82..v125
+	 * only wrote bit 0; v125 BAR0 telemetry confirmed TX current
+	 * pointer (BAR+0x03c) never advanced past base — i.e. zero
+	 * descriptors fetched across 22 xmit attempts.
+	 *
+	 * Why Linux missed this: mts_mac_init writes 0x00010100 to BAR+0x030
+	 * (MTS_MAC_MODE) already, and BAR+0x030 / 0x034 are visible at the
+	 * same value in the Orbis idle snapshot — we assumed they aliased.
+	 * They don't: 0x030 is MAC_MODE config; 0x034 is the TX engine
+	 * control register and needs its own programming.  See Ghidra
+	 * decompile of Orbis mts_mac_init @ 0xffffffffc85ecb60 (writes
+	 * 0x10100 to 0x030) and mts_init_rings_kick @ 0xffffffffc85ef1b0
+	 * (ORs bit 0 to 0x034) — Orbis must also write 0x10100 to 0x034
+	 * somewhere we haven't yet localised, since the snapshot shows
+	 * both registers at 0x00010100 in working state.
+	 *
+	 * Write cfg bits + go bit in one transaction.  After this write the
+	 * read-back should show 0x00010100 (HW clears go, cfg persists).
+	 * Same RX_CTRL pattern is left as-is since RX already works. */
+	{
+		u32 tx_before = readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+		u32 tx_after;
+
+		writel(tx_before | 0x00010101u, mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+		tx_after = readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+		dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+			 "v126: TX_CTRL 0x%08x -> writel(|0x10101) -> 0x%08x (Orbis cfg bits 8+16 + go)\n",
+			 tx_before, tx_after);
+	}
 	writel(readl(mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL) | 0x1, mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL);

 	/*
